{
  "texts": [
    "studied the use of generative AI to simulate patient interactions in problem-based learning tutorials and found that students rated the AI-augmented experience higher in terms of clinical accuracy and teamwork compared to traditional multimedia case materials [78].",
    "However, there was no significant difference in patient history recall between the AI and multimedia case materials.",
    "The AI avatar successfully engaged students and provided accurate case content, but students viewed it as a sophisticated question bank rather than a dynamic patient.",
    "The study concludes that integrating AI early in medical education could improve clinical reasoning and communication skills.",
    "Generative AI can also be used to assist in teaching other clinical skills such as communication and documentation, by establishing a safe setting for practice and offering advice on challenging issues like sharing bad news with empathic language or reducing medical jargon, and enabling students to practice tough conversations, such as those surrounding end-of-life care, thereby helping them develop the communication skills necessary to deliver sensitive information to patients and their families [79,80]."
  ]
}